WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.220 --> 00:00:04.180
LAURIE: Welcome to
Photographers at Google.

00:00:04.180 --> 00:00:07.460
And it is my supreme pleasure
to introduce Karen Hutton.

00:00:07.460 --> 00:00:09.040
She's one of the
most energetic, full

00:00:09.040 --> 00:00:11.090
of life people on the planet.

00:00:11.090 --> 00:00:13.200
Besides being an
amazing photographer,

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:16.010
here are a few things you
might not know about Karen.

00:00:16.010 --> 00:00:19.060
She was an actor-- film,
stage, and television,

00:00:19.060 --> 00:00:21.810
voiceover artist who's done
hundreds of commercials,

00:00:21.810 --> 00:00:23.610
and she's the voice
of Stuck on Earth,

00:00:23.610 --> 00:00:25.490
created by Trey Ratcliff.

00:00:25.490 --> 00:00:29.210
Professional ice-skater and
dancer, a horse trainer,

00:00:29.210 --> 00:00:30.980
creator of Lil Galleries.

00:00:30.980 --> 00:00:33.650
She teaches workshops,
photo workshops,

00:00:33.650 --> 00:00:35.920
does virtual photo walks.

00:00:35.920 --> 00:00:39.300
And her work has been featured
on the "NBC Nightly News",

00:00:39.300 --> 00:00:41.210
and she has a video
chat series called

00:00:41.210 --> 00:00:44.070
The Chat with Karen
Hutton, Sound Byte Insights

00:00:44.070 --> 00:00:46.730
from Some of the Coolest
People on the Planet.

00:00:46.730 --> 00:00:48.540
She also has a list
of firsts on Google+.

00:00:48.540 --> 00:00:53.180
She attended the very
first Google+ Photo Walk.

00:00:53.180 --> 00:00:55.990
She was one of the first people
to join Google+ a couple years

00:00:55.990 --> 00:01:00.400
ago, and she has now over
1.5 million followers.

00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:04.372
She was my first Hangout on
Air for Nik Software at Google.

00:01:04.372 --> 00:01:06.330
And she was also the
first person I interviewed

00:01:06.330 --> 00:01:09.930
for our Google+ Women
in Photography series.

00:01:09.930 --> 00:01:12.690
Now today, Karen
is also a first.

00:01:12.690 --> 00:01:16.260
She's the first woman for our
Photographers at Google Talk

00:01:16.260 --> 00:01:17.570
series.

00:01:17.570 --> 00:01:20.380
Her topic today, she'll be
discussing Signature-- Finding

00:01:20.380 --> 00:01:23.340
Your Soul's Genius and
Voice in your Photography.

00:01:23.340 --> 00:01:26.540
Please give a warm welcome
to the amazing, one and only,

00:01:26.540 --> 00:01:27.680
my friend, Karen Hutton.

00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:29.440
KAREN HUTTON: Thank you.

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:30.760
Thank you, thank you.

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:33.750
I feel exhausted
hearing about my life.

00:01:33.750 --> 00:01:36.900
I'm like, I need a rest.

00:01:36.900 --> 00:01:39.650
So today, I'm going
to tell you a story.

00:01:39.650 --> 00:01:42.320
Because that's what
I do, I tell stories.

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:44.565
And we're going to build
the story together,

00:01:44.565 --> 00:01:45.940
and I'm going to
try and remember

00:01:45.940 --> 00:01:48.560
that for you, it goes this way.

00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:51.260
For me, it goes this way, but
for you, it goes this way.

00:01:51.260 --> 00:01:52.730
So I'm going to go this way.

00:01:52.730 --> 00:01:54.330
So we're going to
build this story.

00:01:54.330 --> 00:01:58.380
How many of you like
to be recognized

00:01:58.380 --> 00:02:01.540
for the things you do
and for your photography?

00:02:01.540 --> 00:02:03.140
I know I do.

00:02:03.140 --> 00:02:04.190
Yes, thank you!

00:02:04.190 --> 00:02:08.350
Some of you didn't raise your
hand, and I find you suspect.

00:02:08.350 --> 00:02:09.090
But that's OK.

00:02:09.090 --> 00:02:10.919
We'll work this out later.

00:02:10.919 --> 00:02:16.700
So recognition and being
noticed, some of us

00:02:16.700 --> 00:02:17.762
feel ashamed about that.

00:02:17.762 --> 00:02:19.220
Oh, I shouldn't
want to be noticed.

00:02:19.220 --> 00:02:20.510
Well guess what?

00:02:20.510 --> 00:02:24.460
Wanting to be seen, and
heard, and felt, and smelled,

00:02:24.460 --> 00:02:30.180
and experienced is one of the
most primal needs of humans,

00:02:30.180 --> 00:02:31.730
of human kind.

00:02:31.730 --> 00:02:35.830
I mean, we're here to be amongst
each other, be in community.

00:02:35.830 --> 00:02:39.910
And not being seen
and recognized

00:02:39.910 --> 00:02:42.380
just goes against
everything we know and love.

00:02:42.380 --> 00:02:48.461
So when it comes to photography,
I, you know, I've coached.

00:02:48.461 --> 00:02:49.960
All these things
that she mentioned,

00:02:49.960 --> 00:02:51.030
I've coached them all, too.

00:02:51.030 --> 00:02:52.613
And we also didn't
talk about the fact

00:02:52.613 --> 00:02:56.430
that I've coached television
news broadcasters for 25 years,

00:02:56.430 --> 00:02:59.230
and done photography
all my life.

00:02:59.230 --> 00:03:03.140
And so everything I've
ever done, oddly enough,

00:03:03.140 --> 00:03:05.230
has been all centered
around, all right,

00:03:05.230 --> 00:03:07.190
what does it really mean?

00:03:07.190 --> 00:03:11.200
What thing can we
bring to everything

00:03:11.200 --> 00:03:13.000
we do that makes
it really special?

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:14.580
That makes it mean something?

00:03:14.580 --> 00:03:18.270
That can be kind of
a souls connection?

00:03:18.270 --> 00:03:21.030
I don't know what it is
about me that just is always

00:03:21.030 --> 00:03:24.350
on this course, but that's the
way it is, so get used to it.

00:03:24.350 --> 00:03:29.500
So my opinion-- that's all
we ever really have, is it,

00:03:29.500 --> 00:03:33.570
our opinion-- is,
you need a signature.

00:03:33.570 --> 00:03:35.600
So what is your signature?

00:03:35.600 --> 00:03:38.505
Now obviously, we kind of know
what a signature is, and you're

00:03:38.505 --> 00:03:40.755
probably all going to laugh
at me because you're like,

00:03:40.755 --> 00:03:41.755
oh, she's such an idiot.

00:03:41.755 --> 00:03:43.230
I know what a signature is.

00:03:43.230 --> 00:03:45.630
And of course, here's
the definition.

00:03:45.630 --> 00:03:49.340
Any unique, distinguishing,
aspect, pattern, feature,

00:03:49.340 --> 00:03:50.425
or mark.

00:03:50.425 --> 00:03:52.870
But keep thinking, we're
going to apply this

00:03:52.870 --> 00:03:57.300
to photography in our story
that we're going to build.

00:03:57.300 --> 00:04:01.950
So the thing about signature
that I have learned

00:04:01.950 --> 00:04:06.790
is that it bears the
stamp of who you are.

00:04:06.790 --> 00:04:09.120
It bears the stamp of
your point of view.

00:04:09.120 --> 00:04:13.800
It bears the stamp of your
soul, what you have to say,

00:04:13.800 --> 00:04:17.670
what you want, you know,
what I want you to feel,

00:04:17.670 --> 00:04:20.339
what I want to feel,
it bears all that.

00:04:20.339 --> 00:04:22.450
That's what a
signature is all about.

00:04:22.450 --> 00:04:25.780
And inasmuch as all we
have, really, to offer

00:04:25.780 --> 00:04:29.211
is us-- is who we are--
that signature really

00:04:29.211 --> 00:04:30.710
needs to be in
everything that we're

00:04:30.710 --> 00:04:32.500
doing if we want
to be recognized.

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:34.440
Because nobody can do
you as well as you.

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:35.423
Nobody can do you.

00:04:35.423 --> 00:04:38.270
Nobody can do me as
well as I can so.

00:04:38.270 --> 00:04:40.740
That's why I'm here,
and not someone else.

00:04:40.740 --> 00:04:43.120
I would have hired
someone, otherwise.

00:04:43.120 --> 00:04:45.810
Kidding!

00:04:45.810 --> 00:04:47.130
So we're going to start here.

00:04:47.130 --> 00:04:49.720
So signature is
what enables someone

00:04:49.720 --> 00:04:51.970
to know that it's you talking.

00:04:51.970 --> 00:04:54.150
You recognize your mother's
voice on the phone,

00:04:54.150 --> 00:04:56.160
you recognize your dog's
footsteps coming down

00:04:56.160 --> 00:04:56.889
the hall way.

00:04:56.889 --> 00:04:58.430
There's a lot of
things about someone

00:04:58.430 --> 00:04:59.888
you recognize--
the way they dress,

00:04:59.888 --> 00:05:02.430
the way they talk, the way they
smell, just the way they are,

00:05:02.430 --> 00:05:03.130
their stamp.

00:05:03.130 --> 00:05:04.520
They're like, I know you.

00:05:04.520 --> 00:05:05.730
Well how do you know you?

00:05:05.730 --> 00:05:07.700
It's all those things, right?

00:05:07.700 --> 00:05:10.310
And it's the glance,
it's the look,

00:05:10.310 --> 00:05:13.410
it's this thing right
here that I'm looking at.

00:05:13.410 --> 00:05:16.107
This worldview that
I see here, that I

00:05:16.107 --> 00:05:18.190
am going to see here in a
minute, that I see here.

00:05:18.190 --> 00:05:19.770
My world view.

00:05:19.770 --> 00:05:21.140
My point of view.

00:05:21.140 --> 00:05:24.380
I learned this from
an amazing voice coach

00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:27.160
that I worked with for a
number of years in Los Angeles.

00:05:27.160 --> 00:05:29.520
She works with
celebrities, she works

00:05:29.520 --> 00:05:31.550
with-- they call her
the voice whisperer.

00:05:31.550 --> 00:05:34.970
Her name is Marice Tobias,
and she uses this term

00:05:34.970 --> 00:05:37.662
when teaching us.

00:05:37.662 --> 00:05:39.370
Her point of view
about it, which I think

00:05:39.370 --> 00:05:41.030
is very true if we
take it from voice

00:05:41.030 --> 00:05:43.340
and put it into
photography, it is

00:05:43.340 --> 00:05:49.390
what it is like to be in
the presence of your voice.

00:05:49.390 --> 00:05:51.757
So when we talk
about a voice, when

00:05:51.757 --> 00:05:53.340
she's talking to us
about voice, we're

00:05:53.340 --> 00:05:56.020
talking about speaking voice.

00:05:56.020 --> 00:06:00.180
But I'm talking to you about
the voice in your photography.

00:06:00.180 --> 00:06:01.290
Your voice.

00:06:01.290 --> 00:06:04.540
So what is it like to be in
the presence of your voice?

00:06:04.540 --> 00:06:07.610
Now, this signature idea
is also what enables you

00:06:07.610 --> 00:06:11.200
to, as the feed comes through
your Google+ stream, you know,

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:13.510
here comes a Trey Ratcliff,
here comes a Thomas Hawk,

00:06:13.510 --> 00:06:15.540
here comes whoever
you follow and admire.

00:06:15.540 --> 00:06:17.710
Oh, I know that work.

00:06:17.710 --> 00:06:19.020
Guess how you know that work?

00:06:19.020 --> 00:06:20.625
Because the signature's in it.

00:06:20.625 --> 00:06:21.830
It's all over it.

00:06:21.830 --> 00:06:22.480
You see it.

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:24.210
You know it.

00:06:24.210 --> 00:06:27.250
That's what we want
in our photography.

00:06:27.250 --> 00:06:29.246
Would you agree
that's a good thing?

00:06:29.246 --> 00:06:30.238
Yeah.

00:06:30.238 --> 00:06:31.230
Good.

00:06:31.230 --> 00:06:33.646
Glad we're on the same page,
because we have a whole story

00:06:33.646 --> 00:06:34.460
here to create.

00:06:34.460 --> 00:06:39.580
So when you talk about
this idea of, what

00:06:39.580 --> 00:06:42.350
is it like to be in the
presence of your voice,

00:06:42.350 --> 00:06:45.710
most great artists
I know of, they're

00:06:45.710 --> 00:06:48.700
always in this state of
like, humble amazement.

00:06:48.700 --> 00:06:53.000
Because they know-- the really
good ones know-- that it's not

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.970
them that's putting the
art-- the photograph

00:06:55.970 --> 00:06:58.740
or the art on the canvas
or making the sculpture--

00:06:58.740 --> 00:07:01.880
they know it is this
spark of divine fire

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:03.310
that is coming through them.

00:07:03.310 --> 00:07:06.150
And that their job is
to stay clear enough

00:07:06.150 --> 00:07:08.877
to allow this thing to happen,
so that when they're done,

00:07:08.877 --> 00:07:10.460
they look at that,
and they're amazed.

00:07:10.460 --> 00:07:11.693
They're like, damn!

00:07:11.693 --> 00:07:14.260
That came through me?

00:07:14.260 --> 00:07:14.760
Right?

00:07:14.760 --> 00:07:16.470
That's art.

00:07:16.470 --> 00:07:18.830
So right here, at the
beginning of our story,

00:07:18.830 --> 00:07:20.310
were taking
photography and we're

00:07:20.310 --> 00:07:21.940
going to talk about it as art.

00:07:21.940 --> 00:07:24.590
Because yes, there's
journalistic, yes,

00:07:24.590 --> 00:07:26.960
there's snapshot at a party.

00:07:26.960 --> 00:07:29.730
But even that can
have a signature.

00:07:29.730 --> 00:07:31.730
And because of what I
want to talk to you about,

00:07:31.730 --> 00:07:34.271
because the amazing thing I've
noticed over the years is that

00:07:34.271 --> 00:07:37.820
people who engage in this
whole signature process end up

00:07:37.820 --> 00:07:40.564
in a different place in
their life people who don't.

00:07:40.564 --> 00:07:41.980
And I have found
that fascinating.

00:07:41.980 --> 00:07:44.600
And it doesn't matter if it's
in photography, in voice,

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:49.010
in acting, in all these things
that I've done, it all the.

00:07:49.010 --> 00:07:50.910
Same it's amazing.

00:07:50.910 --> 00:07:55.800
So a signature cannot be bought.

00:07:55.800 --> 00:07:57.080
It cannot be borrowed.

00:07:57.080 --> 00:07:58.930
O course, when I
first heard about it,

00:07:58.930 --> 00:08:00.830
Marice was telling us
all about signature

00:08:00.830 --> 00:08:02.580
and I got so nervous,
because I was like,

00:08:02.580 --> 00:08:04.980
oh my God, now I
need a signature.

00:08:04.980 --> 00:08:06.020
Where do I get it?

00:08:06.020 --> 00:08:06.570
Do I buy one?

00:08:06.570 --> 00:08:07.457
Is there a sale?

00:08:07.457 --> 00:08:08.540
Is there something online?

00:08:08.540 --> 00:08:10.880
Can I, uh-- but no.

00:08:10.880 --> 00:08:12.590
It's actually kind
of this inner process

00:08:12.590 --> 00:08:16.060
that you have to go
through to bring it out.

00:08:16.060 --> 00:08:20.535
And in photography, if we break
it down to make it simple,

00:08:20.535 --> 00:08:22.660
because what I'm saying is
all very good in theory,

00:08:22.660 --> 00:08:25.190
but what does it really mean?

00:08:25.190 --> 00:08:27.530
There are elements
to a signature.

00:08:27.530 --> 00:08:29.590
There are things you
already know about yourself

00:08:29.590 --> 00:08:31.790
that, if you focus on
them in your photography,

00:08:31.790 --> 00:08:35.500
it already creates an
interesting, different, unique

00:08:35.500 --> 00:08:36.380
point of view.

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:39.419
So I'm going to show
some photos of my own.

00:08:39.419 --> 00:08:41.239
Not because like, I'm
the best photographer

00:08:41.239 --> 00:08:42.280
on the face of the earth.

00:08:42.280 --> 00:08:43.054
I'm OK.

00:08:43.054 --> 00:08:45.220
But I have a signature,
I've thought a lot about it.

00:08:45.220 --> 00:08:49.040
And I chose some photos that
show it in a really simple way

00:08:49.040 --> 00:08:51.130
so that we can have a
discussion about it.

00:08:51.130 --> 00:08:54.500
So this is one.

00:08:54.500 --> 00:08:58.360
Now, I mentioned before,
I am always on a journey.

00:08:58.360 --> 00:09:01.230
I didn't use that word,
but I'm a journey person.

00:09:01.230 --> 00:09:03.200
I'm always going
from here to there.

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:04.110
I can't stand still.

00:09:04.110 --> 00:09:06.700
I don't think that's our
nature to stand still.

00:09:06.700 --> 00:09:10.400
I think evolution is
just part of who we are.

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:14.500
So one of the elements
that tends to show itself

00:09:14.500 --> 00:09:16.650
over and over are,
we're going somewhere.

00:09:16.650 --> 00:09:18.110
So I love leading lines.

00:09:18.110 --> 00:09:19.480
So we have leading lines.

00:09:19.480 --> 00:09:20.800
We';re going on a journey.

00:09:20.800 --> 00:09:23.470
We have the mystical mist.

00:09:23.470 --> 00:09:25.800
I love the mystical mist.

00:09:25.800 --> 00:09:30.410
I require a certain amount
of mystical mist in my life.

00:09:30.410 --> 00:09:32.080
In this case, we
had a mystical mist,

00:09:32.080 --> 00:09:33.470
because there was some fog.

00:09:33.470 --> 00:09:35.980
But there wasn't enough,
so I added a little bit.

00:09:35.980 --> 00:09:38.030
And I don't mind doing
that, because this

00:09:38.030 --> 00:09:41.500
is my expression of my reality
and I'm going to put it out

00:09:41.500 --> 00:09:44.160
there and that's what
I'm going to roll with.

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:45.650
I love the light from above.

00:09:45.650 --> 00:09:46.935
I love the pop of color.

00:09:46.935 --> 00:09:49.410
I love that it's
warm and then cool.

00:09:49.410 --> 00:09:51.750
And I love that it just
makes you want to go and see

00:09:51.750 --> 00:09:53.540
what's around the
corner, because I

00:09:53.540 --> 00:09:55.050
think that is the
nature of life.

00:09:55.050 --> 00:09:57.680
And that is how I live
my life and that's

00:09:57.680 --> 00:09:59.310
how I think about it.

00:09:59.310 --> 00:10:01.160
So, boom.

00:10:01.160 --> 00:10:05.340
I would say of many of
the photos that I have,

00:10:05.340 --> 00:10:09.630
this has probably been one
of the more shared photos,

00:10:09.630 --> 00:10:12.720
probably, on the internet.

00:10:12.720 --> 00:10:15.170
So it must strike a
chord with people.

00:10:15.170 --> 00:10:17.714
I know it's got
more of the elements

00:10:17.714 --> 00:10:20.380
with-- between light, and magic,
and mystery, and leading lines,

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:21.860
and the journey,
and the colors, I

00:10:21.860 --> 00:10:24.240
would say it has
probably the most

00:10:24.240 --> 00:10:29.400
elements of my own signature
in it of most photos that I do.

00:10:29.400 --> 00:10:31.850
I don't really know why
it got shared so much,

00:10:31.850 --> 00:10:33.314
but anyway, it did.

00:10:33.314 --> 00:10:33.980
So there you go.

00:10:33.980 --> 00:10:37.850
And it's in the +1
collection book.

00:10:37.850 --> 00:10:39.160
I believe it's on Page 10.

00:10:39.160 --> 00:10:41.350
I'm not sure.

00:10:41.350 --> 00:10:43.030
I could be wrong about that.

00:10:43.030 --> 00:10:44.140
I knew it at one point.

00:10:44.140 --> 00:10:47.320
Anyway, so then, perspective.

00:10:47.320 --> 00:10:49.825
And leading lines.

00:10:49.825 --> 00:10:51.450
If you know your
signature and you know

00:10:51.450 --> 00:10:54.540
you're the kind of person that
looks at things differently,

00:10:54.540 --> 00:10:58.060
than that's going to inform
where you hold your camera.

00:10:58.060 --> 00:10:59.450
You can hold it here.

00:10:59.450 --> 00:11:01.060
You know, if the
normal shot is like,

00:11:01.060 --> 00:11:02.890
I'm going to shoot
all of you, but now I

00:11:02.890 --> 00:11:04.430
want to get a
different perspective,

00:11:04.430 --> 00:11:05.270
maybe I'll hold it up.

00:11:05.270 --> 00:11:06.269
Maybe I'll hold it down.

00:11:06.269 --> 00:11:08.810
Maybe I'll hold it sideways.

00:11:08.810 --> 00:11:10.620
How you see the world
will inform you.

00:11:10.620 --> 00:11:12.290
So this is in Florence.

00:11:12.290 --> 00:11:14.940
And it was a lovely
shot, holding

