00:22:48.960 --> 00:22:52.420
So when we're talking
this way, we're

00:22:52.420 --> 00:22:55.840
talking about
photography as art.

00:22:55.840 --> 00:22:57.760
So I have-- I never
remember this,

00:22:57.760 --> 00:23:00.780
I always have to read
it-- the definition of art

00:23:00.780 --> 00:23:04.960
is the expression or application
of human creative skill

00:23:04.960 --> 00:23:10.210
and imagination, producing works
to be appreciated primarily

00:23:10.210 --> 00:23:14.760
for their beauty
or emotional power.

00:23:14.760 --> 00:23:18.620
So art values beauty
and emotional power.

00:23:18.620 --> 00:23:22.460
Now, I think we all know
what's beautiful to us.

00:23:22.460 --> 00:23:24.434
I think it's undervalued
in our society,

00:23:24.434 --> 00:23:27.100
and I think there was a point in
history where that decision was

00:23:27.100 --> 00:23:32.730
made to split off
between science and art.

00:23:32.730 --> 00:23:35.390
That's a history lesson, we
won't go into that today.

00:23:35.390 --> 00:23:36.180
That's tomorrow.

00:23:36.180 --> 00:23:36.680
Kidding!

00:23:36.680 --> 00:23:39.250
Don't come back here
tomorrow looking for that.

00:23:39.250 --> 00:23:42.620
So the thing about
art, though, art--

00:23:42.620 --> 00:23:49.100
I'm gonna actually put this on
the screen-- art lets us dream.

00:23:49.100 --> 00:23:54.250
So art is a place we go when
we want something better.

00:23:54.250 --> 00:23:57.710
Like I mentioned before,
our spark of divine fire.

00:23:57.710 --> 00:23:59.560
The place where we go
for something better,

00:23:59.560 --> 00:24:04.220
for our higher view, for ah,
more, what more could there be?

00:24:04.220 --> 00:24:05.270
We go to art.

00:24:05.270 --> 00:24:07.750
And by art, it
could be your life,

00:24:07.750 --> 00:24:11.190
it could be your photography,
it could be something you do.

00:24:11.190 --> 00:24:15.820
But artful living, that is a
living your life as an art,

00:24:15.820 --> 00:24:16.320
right?

00:24:16.320 --> 00:24:20.620
And that's kind of
what I'm talking about.

00:24:20.620 --> 00:24:25.161
And the thing of it
is, this is not new.

00:24:25.161 --> 00:24:27.160
I was curious to see--
oh, this does look good.

00:24:27.160 --> 00:24:30.810
So Rumi-- how many of you know
Rumi, the mystic and poet,

00:24:30.810 --> 00:24:34.000
right, from the 1,200s,
the 13th century.

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:36.250
He said, "Let yourself
be silently drawn

00:24:36.250 --> 00:24:39.740
by the strange pull of
what you really love.

00:24:39.740 --> 00:24:42.757
It will not lead you astray."

00:24:42.757 --> 00:24:44.090
I think that's really important.

00:24:44.090 --> 00:24:46.470
That was how many years ago?

00:24:46.470 --> 00:24:48.711
And he was telling people this.

00:24:48.711 --> 00:24:49.210
Why?

00:24:49.210 --> 00:24:51.311
Because I think people
make choices about,

00:24:51.311 --> 00:24:52.685
well, I'm going
to feel this way,

00:24:52.685 --> 00:24:55.330
or I'm going to do this,
because it will get me that.

00:24:55.330 --> 00:24:56.750
Something on the outside.

00:24:56.750 --> 00:25:00.320
When in fact, the thing
that gets you recognized,

00:25:00.320 --> 00:25:02.600
the thing that leads
you to something better,

00:25:02.600 --> 00:25:05.730
or to a better
photograph, is what

00:25:05.730 --> 00:25:08.200
you love about the photograph,
about your perspective,

00:25:08.200 --> 00:25:10.330
about your processing,
about how you're

00:25:10.330 --> 00:25:14.110
going to make your voice, which
is what signature is leading us

00:25:14.110 --> 00:25:16.660
to-- how you're going to
make that heard, and seen,

00:25:16.660 --> 00:25:18.870
and smelled, and felt, and
every other sense that you

00:25:18.870 --> 00:25:21.390
can possibly pack in.

00:25:21.390 --> 00:25:24.550
The late 1800s, James
Allen, who was a writer,

00:25:24.550 --> 00:25:27.200
he wrote about-- he wrote
kind of, not a spiritual list,

00:25:27.200 --> 00:25:29.130
but he wrote about--
I guess you'd call him

00:25:29.130 --> 00:25:32.050
a self-help author of the 1800s.

00:25:32.050 --> 00:25:34.590
"The vision that you
glorify in your mind.

00:25:34.590 --> 00:25:39.350
the ideal that you enthrone
in your heart, this

00:25:39.350 --> 00:25:40.940
you will build your life by."

00:25:40.940 --> 00:25:41.720
No matter what.

00:25:41.720 --> 00:25:43.240
Even if you don't choose to.

00:25:43.240 --> 00:25:46.240
Whatever you think about
and feel about the most,

00:25:46.240 --> 00:25:48.290
that is what you will
build your life by.

00:25:48.290 --> 00:25:51.100
That is what you will become.

00:25:51.100 --> 00:25:55.130
So if art, carried all the
way back to your photographs,

00:25:55.130 --> 00:25:58.760
allows you to dream, to
dream of something better,

00:25:58.760 --> 00:26:01.620
to dream of wow, I didn't
think of doing it like this.

00:26:01.620 --> 00:26:02.310
What if I do?

00:26:02.310 --> 00:26:05.470
That process starts to find
its way into your life.

00:26:05.470 --> 00:26:07.400
And this is one of the
real big powers, to me,

00:26:07.400 --> 00:26:10.450
of photography and art.

00:26:10.450 --> 00:26:12.180
More recently,
Gloria Steinem said,

00:26:12.180 --> 00:26:15.970
"Without leaps of
imagination or dreaming,

00:26:15.970 --> 00:26:18.910
we lose the excitement
of possibilities."

00:26:18.910 --> 00:26:20.910
And that's what we're
really talking about here,

00:26:20.910 --> 00:26:22.990
is having possibilities.

00:26:22.990 --> 00:26:26.605
"Dreaming, after all,
is a form of planning."

00:26:26.605 --> 00:26:28.900
Which I love.

00:26:28.900 --> 00:26:29.430
I love that.

00:26:31.960 --> 00:26:37.130
So what would you attempt to do
if you knew you could not fail?

00:26:37.130 --> 00:26:39.515
Whether it's photography,
whether it's life.

00:26:42.870 --> 00:26:46.300
What dream would you have
about this photograph,

00:26:46.300 --> 00:26:48.610
about this vision, about
what you want to do,

00:26:48.610 --> 00:26:53.520
and who you want to become,
if you knew you couldn't fail?

00:26:53.520 --> 00:26:55.680
So yeah, you thought
we were going

00:26:55.680 --> 00:26:57.490
to talk about
photography, didn't you?

00:26:57.490 --> 00:26:59.360
Ha!

00:26:59.360 --> 00:27:03.450
So this brings us to story.

00:27:03.450 --> 00:27:05.490
We use our photographs
to tell a story.

00:27:05.490 --> 00:27:06.590
We dream of a story.

00:27:06.590 --> 00:27:08.340
Like, I mean, I just
took you through some

00:27:08.340 --> 00:27:09.940
of my crazy photographs, right?

00:27:09.940 --> 00:27:11.315
Oh, I think I'll
do this with it.

00:27:11.315 --> 00:27:12.880
Because it's a story.

00:27:12.880 --> 00:27:15.400
How many of you heard Alan
Shapiro's talk last month

00:27:15.400 --> 00:27:16.590
about words?

00:27:16.590 --> 00:27:17.140
Yeah.

00:27:17.140 --> 00:27:19.690
If you haven't seen it, you
should go back and watch it.

00:27:19.690 --> 00:27:23.120
It's fantastic, where he talks
about words and the importance

00:27:23.120 --> 00:27:26.630
of words with your photographs.

00:27:26.630 --> 00:27:29.970
I think there are, in fact,
three kinds of stories.

00:27:29.970 --> 00:27:32.890
I think words are huge,
and I think beyond that,

00:27:32.890 --> 00:27:33.650
we have stories.

00:27:33.650 --> 00:27:35.760
And I think there
are three kinds.

00:27:35.760 --> 00:27:40.450
And I think we have stories
that give, stories that take,

00:27:40.450 --> 00:27:43.980
and stories just for
the facts, ma'am.

00:27:43.980 --> 00:27:47.320
Examples of stories that give--
stories that give are like,

00:27:47.320 --> 00:27:50.850
throughout history we have
our ancestors and families

00:27:50.850 --> 00:27:54.460
and civilizations who have
passed on, either through

00:27:54.460 --> 00:27:56.710
pictographs or whether it's
written or through song

00:27:56.710 --> 00:27:59.960
or whatever, whatever they
did, they told us how to --

00:27:59.960 --> 00:28:04.012
what they encountered, what
to watch out for, how to have

00:28:04.012 --> 00:28:06.220
families, how to have fun,
how to laugh, what to eat,

00:28:06.220 --> 00:28:07.000
what not to eat.

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:09.415
All those things, those
are stories that give.

00:28:09.415 --> 00:28:11.550
They help us live.

00:28:11.550 --> 00:28:13.960
Other stories that give
from more modern times

00:28:13.960 --> 00:28:15.660
are stories of inspiration.

00:28:15.660 --> 00:28:18.710
Stories that like, wow,
I had this thing happen.

00:28:18.710 --> 00:28:21.800
I lost my leg, but this
is how I overcame it.

00:28:21.800 --> 00:28:24.320
Or had this bad thing happen,
but this is what I did.

00:28:24.320 --> 00:28:25.980
This is how I made it work.

00:28:25.980 --> 00:28:27.980
Stories that lift you up.

00:28:27.980 --> 00:28:29.640
Stories that inspire.

00:28:29.640 --> 00:28:31.120
Stories that empower.

00:28:31.120 --> 00:28:33.580
Those are stories that give.

00:28:33.580 --> 00:28:35.880
Same with photographs.

00:28:35.880 --> 00:28:39.130
Stories that take--
good example-- this

00:28:39.130 --> 00:28:40.445
is a really good example.

00:28:40.445 --> 00:28:41.870
You can all relate to this one.

00:28:41.870 --> 00:28:46.090
Is, you have a voice in
your head that says, God,

00:28:46.090 --> 00:28:47.160
you're stupid.

00:28:47.160 --> 00:28:49.800
Oh, my God, why
did you say that?

00:28:49.800 --> 00:28:51.240
You are so fat.

00:28:51.240 --> 00:28:53.400
Why aren't you exercising?

00:28:53.400 --> 00:28:54.660
You are so lazy.

00:28:54.660 --> 00:28:56.480
Oh my God, that was a
stupid thing to say.

00:28:56.480 --> 00:28:59.660
Have any of you ever
heard any of these?

00:28:59.660 --> 00:29:03.910
You're all kind of going,
no, yes, yes, no, yes.

00:29:03.910 --> 00:29:05.060
We all have.

00:29:05.060 --> 00:29:06.540
That's our critical
voice inside,

00:29:06.540 --> 00:29:09.630
and it tells you a
story about yourself.

00:29:09.630 --> 00:29:12.670
It tells you a story about
yourself that in many cases,

00:29:12.670 --> 00:29:15.420
people assume is right--
or maybe they don't even

00:29:15.420 --> 00:29:16.217
question it.

00:29:16.217 --> 00:29:17.300
They just start living it.

00:29:17.300 --> 00:29:19.390
Oh my God, that's true, OK.

00:29:19.390 --> 00:29:21.100
So pretty soon, that
becomes the filter--

00:29:21.100 --> 00:29:23.940
the lens-- through which
you live your life,

00:29:23.940 --> 00:29:26.590
process your photos,
take a photograph.

00:29:26.590 --> 00:29:29.690
I'm never successful
because-- I could never

00:29:29.690 --> 00:29:32.260
win because-- I just
wanted it to be this way,

00:29:32.260 --> 00:29:36.200
but it can't because, whatever,
oh my God, I'm tired now.

00:29:36.200 --> 00:29:37.690
So stories that take.

00:29:37.690 --> 00:29:40.190
On the outside,
pretty much any story

00:29:40.190 --> 00:29:43.070
that you hear from someone else
that makes you feel like crap?

00:29:43.070 --> 00:29:44.850
That's a story that takes.

00:29:44.850 --> 00:29:45.810
It's taking away.

00:29:45.810 --> 00:29:47.540
It disempowers.

00:29:47.540 --> 00:29:48.810
It makes you less than.

00:29:48.810 --> 00:29:49.780
It makes you doubt.

00:29:49.780 --> 00:29:52.700
It makes you feel lousy.

00:29:52.700 --> 00:29:56.220
Those are stories that take.

00:29:56.220 --> 00:30:00.650
I had a very incredible mentor
in my life who was my voice

00:30:00.650 --> 00:30:03.840
coach, and I did personal
development with her

00:30:03.840 --> 00:30:05.710
for many, many years.

00:30:05.710 --> 00:30:07.645
So I think it might
have been-- it

00:30:07.645 --> 00:30:09.640
might have been 30 years
ago-- she said to me,

00:30:09.640 --> 00:30:11.570
we were talking about
the inner voice, right,

00:30:11.570 --> 00:30:13.410
the one that was stories.

00:30:13.410 --> 00:30:17.690
She said to me, she said,
if it tells you a story

00:30:17.690 --> 00:30:21.670
and it makes you
feel bad, it's a lie.

00:30:21.670 --> 00:30:23.340
Pure and simple.

00:30:23.340 --> 00:30:25.460
No ifs, ands, or buts.

00:30:25.460 --> 00:30:29.500
If it makes you feel
bad, it is a lie.

00:30:29.500 --> 00:30:32.680
And 30 years ago, I
said, that's a lie.

00:30:32.680 --> 00:30:35.267
I just can't believe it's that
simple because blah, blah,

00:30:35.267 --> 00:30:35.975
blah, blah, blah.

00:30:35.975 --> 00:30:37.460
Because I had so many stories.

00:30:37.460 --> 00:30:41.760
Well, I've field tested
this sucker for a long time,

00:30:41.760 --> 00:30:45.400
and I'm now on the page
where I realize she's right.

00:30:45.400 --> 00:30:47.820
If it makes you feel
bad, it is a lie

00:30:47.820 --> 00:30:50.970
and is a story that takes--
and give it the boot.

00:30:50.970 --> 00:30:52.950
Whatever you've got to do.

00:30:52.950 --> 00:30:56.470
So art allows us to
find those, allows

00:30:56.470 --> 00:30:58.080
us to discover
those for yourself.

00:30:58.080 --> 00:31:00.490
Because if you're in your
artistic state, and let's

00:31:00.490 --> 00:31:03.610
say you're processing-- how
many of you process photos?

00:31:03.610 --> 00:31:05.170
Yeah, OK, so we're
on the page here.

00:31:05.170 --> 00:31:06.310
I wondered about that.

00:31:06.310 --> 00:31:08.170
So you're processing
the photo and you

00:31:08.170 --> 00:31:11.414
let yourself go in this
zone where, OK, this

00:31:11.414 --> 00:31:12.580
would be beautiful, or this.

00:31:12.580 --> 00:31:13.830
I feel like trying this.

00:31:13.830 --> 00:31:14.700
Or let's try this.

00:31:14.700 --> 00:31:17.570
And it starts to feel
amazing, and all of a sudden,

00:31:17.570 --> 00:31:19.919
you find yourself, like
it's been a hard day,

00:31:19.919 --> 00:31:21.210
but now you're having some fun.

00:31:21.210 --> 00:31:23.550
And oh, my God, you're
in your happy place,

00:31:23.550 --> 00:31:25.910
and wow, I never
thought of doing that.

00:31:25.910 --> 00:31:29.300
And you're in this
sort of uplifted place,

00:31:29.300 --> 00:31:32.870
you start to realize,
wow, the rest of the time,

00:31:32.870 --> 00:31:34.290
I feel really crappy.

00:31:34.290 --> 00:31:35.360
Why is that?

00:31:35.360 --> 00:31:38.112
You almost need the
contrast to even find out

00:31:38.112 --> 00:31:39.570
how much you're
beating yourself up

00:31:39.570 --> 00:31:42.950
or how much you believe
bad stories, or whatever,

00:31:42.950 --> 00:31:48.120
to know that there's another
choice that you could make.

00:31:48.120 --> 00:31:49.970
Stories just for the
facts have their place.

00:31:49.970 --> 00:31:51.428
They're not
particularly emotional.

00:31:51.428 --> 00:31:53.940
The first two are very
emotionally loaded.

00:31:53.940 --> 00:31:57.210
The third one is like, what's
the story of this photograph?

00:31:57.210 --> 00:31:57.900
What did you do?

00:31:57.900 --> 00:32:03.990
Well, I used my Canon 5D Mark
III, I used my 24-70 2.8.

00:32:03.990 --> 00:32:05.870
These settings, I shot
it HDR, and then I

00:32:05.870 --> 00:32:07.328
processed it and
used the software.

00:32:07.328 --> 00:32:10.150
And that was how I did this
photo-- which is valuable.

00:32:10.150 --> 00:32:11.240
Some people need that.

00:32:11.240 --> 00:32:13.890
The DMV needs to know what
happened in the intersection

00:32:13.890 --> 00:32:15.470
when your car got crunched.

00:32:15.470 --> 00:32:17.920
Those are important stories,
but they're not emotional.

00:32:17.920 --> 00:32:21.650
They're not going to inform
you the way these other two do.

00:32:21.650 --> 00:32:24.430
And since we're talking art--
so we started with signature,

00:32:24.430 --> 00:32:27.770
right, and we talked about art
and it allows you to dream,

00:32:27.770 --> 00:32:29.439
so now we're in this
part of the story.

00:32:29.439 --> 00:32:30.980
And now we're coming
over here, we're

00:32:30.980 --> 00:32:38.910
coming into another place of
the story, which is, what if?

00:32:38.910 --> 00:32:40.820
What if is one of
my favorite-- I

00:32:40.820 --> 00:32:43.350
always call it a game
because I like to have fun--

00:32:43.350 --> 00:32:47.060
but it's one of the most
powerful games, tools,

00:32:47.060 --> 00:32:49.390
out there.

00:32:49.390 --> 00:32:57.800
What if allows you to
play a different game.

00:32:57.800 --> 00:33:02.650
What if allows you to say, well,
this is how it seems to be.

00:33:02.650 --> 00:33:04.820
But what if it were like this?

00:33:04.820 --> 00:33:06.680
What if I tried that?

00:33:06.680 --> 00:33:10.470
It starts to lift the lid off
of-- it's always like this

00:33:10.470 --> 00:33:12.430
and I'm always in pain, right?

00:33:12.430 --> 00:33:16.240
And it allows you to start to
crack open some perspective.

00:33:16.240 --> 00:33:17.310
Where's that microphone?

00:33:17.310 --> 00:33:19.020
I'm going to show
you a video, but I

00:33:19.020 --> 00:33:20.870
have to do it a certain way.

00:33:20.870 --> 00:33:21.550
It's here?

00:33:21.550 --> 00:33:22.050
Oh.

00:33:22.050 --> 00:33:24.480
Is it on?

00:33:24.480 --> 00:33:33.235
So I'm going to play you
a story about possibility,

00:33:33.235 --> 00:33:33.985
about perspective.

