00:50:53.980 --> 00:50:55.247
That's my background.

00:50:55.247 --> 00:50:56.330
I can see black and white.

00:50:56.330 --> 00:50:59.830
I can be all art and I can
be all traditional, but why?

00:50:59.830 --> 00:51:02.220
I know, I have something to
say, and I'm going to say it,

00:51:02.220 --> 00:51:03.230
dammit.

00:51:03.230 --> 00:51:05.820
So quit arguing with me.

00:51:05.820 --> 00:51:10.019
So this is-- I have been
doing a show called, "The Chat

00:51:10.019 --> 00:51:12.310
with Karen Hutton", Sound
byte-sized insights from some

00:51:12.310 --> 00:51:14.320
of the coolest
people on the planet.

00:51:14.320 --> 00:51:16.440
Nichole Young has been on there.

00:51:16.440 --> 00:51:18.410
Lauren Rubin has been on there.

00:51:18.410 --> 00:51:23.380
And the reason I'm doing it
is because I look around.

00:51:23.380 --> 00:51:26.550
I look around at
photographers and their issues

00:51:26.550 --> 00:51:28.190
and what they're
trying to accomplish.

00:51:28.190 --> 00:51:30.110
And they want to be more,
they want to be bigger.

00:51:30.110 --> 00:51:31.901
They want to be this,
they want to be that.

00:51:31.901 --> 00:51:33.240
We've got to cross train.

00:51:33.240 --> 00:51:37.070
I've been fortunate to do so
many things-- so many things--

00:51:37.070 --> 00:51:40.330
that I've discovered the thread
that pulls them all together.

00:51:40.330 --> 00:51:42.730
And it's the stuff we're
talking about right now.

00:51:42.730 --> 00:51:45.490
So on "The Chat", my
goal is to develop,

00:51:45.490 --> 00:51:47.580
for however long
I do this show, is

00:51:47.580 --> 00:51:49.240
to develop a library
of people who

00:51:49.240 --> 00:51:53.170
are living their life
artfully, thoughtfully,

00:51:53.170 --> 00:51:55.400
in a way that perhaps
isn't traditional.

00:51:55.400 --> 00:51:59.169
But who are finding a way
to take that part of them

00:51:59.169 --> 00:52:01.710
that they're passionate about--
these could be photographers,

00:52:01.710 --> 00:52:05.450
they could be musicians,
singers, businesspeople,

00:52:05.450 --> 00:52:07.900
they can be anyone who is
living their life a little bit

00:52:07.900 --> 00:52:08.400
differently.

00:52:08.400 --> 00:52:11.820
We're going to have a short
chat, it's a 15-minute show.

00:52:11.820 --> 00:52:14.510
And share, OK, so what
have you discovered?

00:52:14.510 --> 00:52:15.460
What did you find out?

00:52:15.460 --> 00:52:16.260
You know how when
you get together?

00:52:16.260 --> 00:52:17.760
What did you find
out along the way?

00:52:17.760 --> 00:52:19.530
I want to steal from that.

00:52:19.530 --> 00:52:20.900
That's the intent behind there.

00:52:20.900 --> 00:52:22.080
And that's why.

00:52:22.080 --> 00:52:24.130
Because these are
people who have taken

00:52:24.130 --> 00:52:26.770
those dreams and have put
them out into the world.

00:52:26.770 --> 00:52:28.270
How did they do that?

00:52:28.270 --> 00:52:28.950
We want to know.

00:52:31.460 --> 00:52:34.850
So in moving toward
wrapping this thing up,

00:52:34.850 --> 00:52:39.210
our story signature, we dream,
we what if, we actually do it.

00:52:39.210 --> 00:52:40.350
Now we're doing it.

00:52:40.350 --> 00:52:42.280
This is when it
informs your life.

00:52:42.280 --> 00:52:45.000
Because it's never enough just
to process a photo this way.

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:46.470
You feel so fricking
good, you want

00:52:46.470 --> 00:52:48.320
to do it in your whole life.

00:52:48.320 --> 00:52:52.954
So this then becomes,
what is your legacy?

00:52:52.954 --> 00:52:53.870
You're all very young.

00:52:53.870 --> 00:52:57.070
Most of you here
are younger than me.

00:52:57.070 --> 00:52:59.050
I'm older than you think.

00:52:59.050 --> 00:53:00.470
And I'm at a point
now in my life

00:53:00.470 --> 00:53:02.829
where-- in the
beginning of my life,

00:53:02.829 --> 00:53:05.120
I said, oh my God, there's
so many things I want to do,

00:53:05.120 --> 00:53:05.940
I've got to do them all.

00:53:05.940 --> 00:53:08.060
That's why Laurie read
such a long list of things.

00:53:08.060 --> 00:53:09.870
Because when I was
really young, I said,

00:53:09.870 --> 00:53:10.780
I'm going to do
all these things.

00:53:10.780 --> 00:53:12.350
Now have to do these
when I'm young,

00:53:12.350 --> 00:53:13.480
because when I get
to be this age,

00:53:13.480 --> 00:53:14.730
I'm not going to have
good knees, so I'm

00:53:14.730 --> 00:53:16.688
going to be able-- you
know, so I kind of like,

00:53:16.688 --> 00:53:18.610
have worked my way
through my list.

00:53:18.610 --> 00:53:20.896
Now I'm at a point
where I'm like, OK,

00:53:20.896 --> 00:53:22.660
what difference did it all make?

00:53:22.660 --> 00:53:26.430
What can I do to help people
who are behind me coming through

00:53:26.430 --> 00:53:28.090
to get here faster?

00:53:28.090 --> 00:53:30.010
Why do they have to
suffer the way I did?

00:53:30.010 --> 00:53:33.090
I had some amazing mentors--
some amazing people

00:53:33.090 --> 00:53:34.760
in my life who
showed me the way.

00:53:34.760 --> 00:53:38.220
In elders who lived
by vision and who

00:53:38.220 --> 00:53:39.830
created their life
in a certain way

00:53:39.830 --> 00:53:42.360
and informed my art and my life.

00:53:42.360 --> 00:53:43.940
That's kind of who I want to be.

00:53:43.940 --> 00:53:46.190
If I'm talking about light,
and journey, and lines,

00:53:46.190 --> 00:53:49.760
and so on and so forth, what
is my legacy going to be?

00:53:49.760 --> 00:53:51.570
And it shows up in my art work.

00:53:51.570 --> 00:53:54.000
It absolutely shows
up in my photography.

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:56.760
I'll pass up shots because
I'm like, that's a nice shot,

00:53:56.760 --> 00:53:58.820
but what's the point?

00:53:58.820 --> 00:53:59.617
What's the story?

00:53:59.617 --> 00:54:00.700
I'm always walking around.

00:54:00.700 --> 00:54:02.770
If I see something that
attracts me, and I go,

00:54:02.770 --> 00:54:03.790
OK, OK, this is cool.

00:54:03.790 --> 00:54:05.070
This is cool, but
what's the story?

00:54:05.070 --> 00:54:05.778
What's the story?

00:54:05.778 --> 00:54:06.700
What's the story?

00:54:06.700 --> 00:54:09.040
And that tells me
where to put my camera.

00:54:09.040 --> 00:54:13.342
And then I most often see it
processed, but sometimes not.

00:54:13.342 --> 00:54:15.925
Sometimes I just know the vibe,
and I know if I shoot it right

00:54:15.925 --> 00:54:18.740
and compose it right,
it's going to talk to me.

00:54:18.740 --> 00:54:21.330
You all know now,
that actually happens.

00:54:21.330 --> 00:54:24.990
It's going to talk to me
when I go to process it.

00:54:24.990 --> 00:54:31.970
So you and your
photography-- I challenge you

00:54:31.970 --> 00:54:33.760
to this-- what
will be your story?

00:54:36.115 --> 00:54:37.240
What are you going to tell?

00:54:37.240 --> 00:54:38.580
What words are you going to use?

00:54:38.580 --> 00:54:40.990
How is it going to
inform your life?

00:54:40.990 --> 00:54:43.590
How are you going to
start seeing the world?

00:54:43.590 --> 00:54:44.960
This is the gift that we have.

00:54:44.960 --> 00:54:48.046
Artists have to take weeks, and
months, and years, sometimes

00:54:48.046 --> 00:54:48.920
to create their work.

00:54:48.920 --> 00:54:51.310
All we got to do is
hold up a camera.

00:54:51.310 --> 00:54:53.807
What's the story?

00:54:53.807 --> 00:54:55.890
What difference you're
going to make to the people

00:54:55.890 --> 00:54:57.014
who come along behind you?

00:54:57.014 --> 00:54:58.680
And how are you going
to tell that story

00:54:58.680 --> 00:55:00.179
through your
photographs, which will

00:55:00.179 --> 00:55:01.470
evolve as you go through life?

00:55:01.470 --> 00:55:02.352
It'll change.

00:55:02.352 --> 00:55:03.560
Like, I'm all into color now.

00:55:03.560 --> 00:55:04.740
I may go back to
black and white.

00:55:04.740 --> 00:55:06.156
I don't know what
I'm going to do.

00:55:06.156 --> 00:55:09.330
I just know that every
moment I go into a photograph

00:55:09.330 --> 00:55:11.770
and process, there's
this creative muse

00:55:11.770 --> 00:55:14.794
who says, "I'd like some
more texture, please."

00:55:14.794 --> 00:55:15.960
And I give her more texture.

00:55:15.960 --> 00:55:17.260
I don't argue with her anymore.

00:55:17.260 --> 00:55:19.260
And like, I used to say, "Oh,
that's not going to work."

00:55:19.260 --> 00:55:21.020
Because she'll go,
"Fine, whatever."

00:55:21.020 --> 00:55:23.420
And then I don't hear
from her again for a year.

00:55:23.420 --> 00:55:24.550
That's sucks.

00:55:24.550 --> 00:55:30.110
So now, I listen to her.

00:55:30.110 --> 00:55:33.660
So I really believe,
I feel, I experience,

00:55:33.660 --> 00:55:36.510
and I see, that in our
photography and in our art,

00:55:36.510 --> 00:55:40.944
there is the possibility-- maybe
the only possibility you have

00:55:40.944 --> 00:55:42.610
in your life at this
time, I don't know,

00:55:42.610 --> 00:55:46.350
I don't know your lives, but to
allow that spark of divine fire

00:55:46.350 --> 00:55:49.960
to come through you,
inform your art,

00:55:49.960 --> 00:55:51.540
and it will inform your life.

00:55:51.540 --> 00:55:52.760
You'll have no choice.

00:55:52.760 --> 00:55:57.610
So I see that my signature
is my point of view.

00:55:57.610 --> 00:56:05.620
I see that my legacy is actually
my soul's voice enlivened

00:56:05.620 --> 00:56:08.070
by the breath of the divine.

00:56:08.070 --> 00:56:09.790
Oddly enough, I see it that way.

00:56:09.790 --> 00:56:13.820
And that my art and my
photography is my gateway.

00:56:13.820 --> 00:56:16.310
And I'm not going to tell
anybody what to make of it.

00:56:16.310 --> 00:56:17.360
I'm just going to do it.

00:56:17.360 --> 00:56:19.500
I'm just going to show
up with guns blazing

00:56:19.500 --> 00:56:23.550
and do the best I can put
that across and let it go.

00:56:23.550 --> 00:56:26.030
Because I'm not going to
tell you what to think.

00:56:26.030 --> 00:56:31.440
But I'm going to do
my best to share it.

00:56:31.440 --> 00:56:35.120
It was George Bernard Shaw who
said, "I have my own soul--

00:56:35.120 --> 00:56:36.805
my own spark of divine fire."

00:56:36.805 --> 00:56:39.110
And he said it in
"Pygmalion," the book

00:56:39.110 --> 00:56:42.380
that became "My Fair Lady."

00:56:42.380 --> 00:56:44.701
Henry Higgins was all
mad when he said this

00:56:44.701 --> 00:56:46.200
because Eliza had
walked out on him.

00:56:46.200 --> 00:56:48.230
he's like, "You can't
do that to be, me!

00:56:48.230 --> 00:56:49.390
I have my own soul!

00:56:49.390 --> 00:56:52.320
My own spark of divine fire!"

00:56:52.320 --> 00:56:55.010
But it is so true, so applies
to what we're all doing here,

00:56:55.010 --> 00:56:57.950
and to what you're all are doing
at Google, which is incredible.

00:56:57.950 --> 00:57:01.970
And Google+ has changed
so many live-- mine!

00:57:01.970 --> 00:57:04.350
The opportunities and the
things that I think about

00:57:04.350 --> 00:57:08.400
because of Google+ and because
of the spark of divine fire

00:57:08.400 --> 00:57:12.880
that you all have brought
has changed everything.

00:57:12.880 --> 00:57:15.780
So I hope you keep doing it.

00:57:15.780 --> 00:57:18.510
I hope you keep letting
all of us do it.

00:57:18.510 --> 00:57:20.790
And that you just let it
come through and let it

00:57:20.790 --> 00:57:22.860
be whatever it's
going to be next.

00:57:22.860 --> 00:57:25.890
Because it will be amazing.

00:57:25.890 --> 00:57:31.160
And so, the light prevails.

00:57:31.160 --> 00:57:32.450
And thank you.

00:57:32.450 --> 00:57:35.890
I hope you take
that into your life.

00:57:35.890 --> 00:57:36.390
Thanks.

